When a stone can move down (i+1 is '.'), it swaps and sets falling to true, which triggers another iteration of the do-while loop. But the code's TODO section is missing the code to swap the stones and set falling to true. So the missing code is: swap a[i][j] and a[i+1][j], and set falling to true. So, in the code:

if (a[i][j] == '*' && a[i+1][j] == '.') {

   swap(a[i][j], a[i+1][j]);

   falling = true;

} But wait, in C++, to swap two characters, we can do:

std::swap(a[i][j], a[i+1][j]);

But since the strings are mutable (since a is a vector of strings, and we are modifying them), perhaps the code can be written as:

a[i][j] = '.';

a[i+1][j] = '*';

Because swapping is equivalent to moving the stone down and replacing the current cell with '.'. Because when you find a stone at (i,j) and '.' at (i+1,j), you can set (i,j) to '.' and (i+1,j) to '*'. This is perhaps more efficient than swapping, but the end result is the same. So in the code:

if (a[i][j] == '*' && a[i+1][j] == '.') {

   a[i][j] = '.'; 

   a[i+1][j] = '*'; 

   falling = true;

}

This will move the stone down one cell.
